Communicated by:
ProMED

[Data by country, area, or territory for 13 Jun 2022 can be accessed at
https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/2022%20WHO%20Data%20Tables%20JUN13_1655232290.pdf.

- The Americas region reported no cases and deaths during the past 24 hours, having reported more than 158.98 million cases, 2nd to the European region, the most severely affected region.

- The European region reported 55.4% of cases and 29.1% of deaths over the last 24 hours, as the most affected region, with cumulative cases exceeding 222.71 million. Some countries reporting few or no cases in the last 24 hours or longer include the UK, Turkey, Spain, Ukraine, Portugal, Belgium, Switzerland, and Tajikistan, among others. A total of 7 countries reported more than 1000 cases in the past 24 hours; 2 countries reported more than 10 000; 5 reported over 1000 cases, while none reported more than 500 but fewer than 1000 cases.

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 2.3% cases and 2.8%deaths during the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 21.82 million cases. UAE(1249) reported the highest number of cases followed by Bahrain and Saudi Arabia.

- The African region reported no cases and deaths during the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 9.04 million cases.

- The Western Pacific region reported 37.1% of daily case numbers and 58.4% deaths in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 62.06 million cases. China (51 110) reported the highest number of cases over the last 24 hours followed by Australia, Japan, New Zealand, South Korea, Singapore, Malaysia, and Viet Nam.

- The Southeast Asia region reported 5.1% of the daily newly reported cases and 9.6 % of reported deaths in the past 24 hours, having reported a cumulative total of more than 58.25 million cases. India (8084) reported the highest number of cases followed by Thailand (1801) and Indonesia (591). Maldives, North Korea, and Bhutan, among others, did not report cases over the last 24 hours.

On the Overview tab at the WHO source URL, the epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 13 Jun 2022, is an excellent visual representation of the pandemic. - Mod.UBA]

